Our objective is to determine associations between mood and rumination The relevant variables here seem to be ratings of happiness & sadness, and the 8 rumination items

Lets try making 2 models: sad ~ rumination sum, happy ~ rumination sum

But first explore the data a bit

library(tidyverse)
library(ggstance)
library(rmcorr)
library(lme4)
library(ordinal)

Load the data

df = read_csv('baseline_r_20240222.csv')

calculate rumination score sum of all rumination items (5-12)

df = df %>%
  mutate(User_Id = as.factor(User_Id)) %>%
  mutate(rumination = rowSums(select(.,c(
    Start_Feeling_Handle,Start_Feeling_Problems,Start_Feeling_move_forward,
    Start_Feeling_Sensations,Start_Feeling_Again,Start_Feeling_Wanting,
    Start_Feeling_Stuck,Start_Feeling_Negative_Thoughts))
    ))

scatter plot: sad vs.rum fit a regression line for each participant

df %>%
  ggplot(show.legend=F) +
  geom_point(aes(x=rumination,y=Start_Feeling_Sad,color=User_Id),show.legend=F,
             position=ggstance::position_dodgev(height=0.3)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(x=rumination,y=Start_Feeling_Sad,color=User_Id),method="lm",se=F,
              show.legend=F) +
  geom_smooth(aes(x=rumination,y=Start_Feeling_Sad),method="lm",se=F,
              show.legend=F,color="black",linewidth=1.5,linetype=2) +
  labs(title = "Negative mood vs. Rumination", subtitle = "(colored by participant)",
       x="Rumination (sum of rumination items)", y="Sadness Rating (1-5)")

Lets separate the plots by participant

df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=rumination,y=Start_Feeling_Sad,color=User_Id),show.legend=F) +

  facet_wrap(~User_Id) +

rmcorr Lets try repeated measures correlation to evaluate the association between mood and rumination

First, negative mood (sad) correlated with rumination

scorr = rmcorr(
  participant = User_Id, 
  measure1 = rumination, 
  measure2 = Start_Feeling_Sad,
  dataset = df)

scorr
## 
## Repeated measures correlation
## 
## r
## 0.6641496
## 
## degrees of freedom
## 525
## 
## p-value
## 2.480989e-68
## 
## 95% confidence interval
## 0.6135411 0.7093247

A not very useful plot of the model Note that rmcorr allows subjects to have different intercepts, but not slopes

splt_label <- paste0("r = ", round(scorr$r, 3), " (95% CI: [", paste0(round(scorr$CI, 3), collapse = ", "), "])")
#par(mar = rep(2, 4))
plot(scorr, main = splt_label, xlab = "Rumination", ylab = "Sad rating")

Now the same for positive mood

hcorr = rmcorr(

  dataset = df)

lmer

Now lets try some mixed modelling LMM effect of rumination score on sadness rating add random intercept & slope for participant test significance via likelihood ratio

lms_n = lmer(Start_Feeling_Sad ~ 1 + (1 + rumination|User_Id), data = df, REML = FALSE)
lms = lmer(Start_Feeling_Sad ~ rumination + (1 + rumination|User_Id), data = df, REML = FALSE)
summary(lms)

According to these models, there is a significant positive effect of rumination on negative mood & negative effect of rumination on positive mood

BUT! Likert data are ordinal and violate the assumptions of GLM (linear mixed models may or may not be appropriate for ordinal data)

to properly model ordinal data, lets use cumulative linked mixed models from the ordinal r package

first, change dependent variable datatypes to ordinal

df_o = df %>%
  mutate(Start_Feeling_Sad = as.ordered(Start_Feeling_Sad),
         Start_Feeling_Happy = as.ordered(Start_Feeling_Happy))
df_o
## # A tibble: 549  48

model builds similar to lme4

clms_n = clmm(Start_Feeling_Sad ~ 1 + (1 + rumination|User_Id), data = df_o)
clms = clmm(Start_Feeling_Sad ~ rumination + (1 + rumination|User_Id), data = df_o)

Per AIC, there is less unexplained variation when rumination is included in the model compared to when it is not

The chisquared value is significant

All of the approaches show a momentary positive relationship between rumination and negative mood, and a momentary negative relationship between rumination and positive mood
